item.description:
In anticipation of next week&rsquo;s Reproducible Science Hackathon at NESCent, I was thinking about Christie Bahlai&rsquo;s post on &ldquo;Baby steps for the open-curious.&rdquo;
Moving from Ye Olde Standard Computational Science Practice to a fully reproducible workflow seems a monumental task, but partially reproducible is better than not-at-all reproducible, and it&rsquo;d be good to give people some advice on how to get started - to encourage them to get started.
So, I spent some time today writing another of my minimal tutorials, on initial steps towards reproducible research.

I was interested to read C. Titus Brown&rsquo;s recent post, &ldquo;Is version control an electronic lab notebook?&ldquo;
I think version control is really important, and I think all computational scientists should have something equivalent to a lab notebook. But I think of version control as serving needs orthogonal to those served by a lab notebook.
As Titus points out, a traditional lab notebook serves two purposes: provenance and protocol. Version control could be useful for provenance, but I don&rsquo;t really care about provenance.

I was playing Chutes &amp; Ladders with my four-year-old daughter yesterday, and I thought, &ldquo;How long is this going to take?&rdquo;
I saw an interesting mathematical analysis of the game a few years ago, but it seems to be offline, though you can read it via the wayback machine.
But that didn&rsquo;t answer my specific question, namely, &ldquo;How long is this going to take?&rdquo;
So I wrote a bit of R code to simulate the game.
